SOLID Principles (Tabular Explanation)
Principle	Full Form	Meaning	Simple Idea
S	Single Responsibility Principle	A class should have only one responsibility	One class → one job
O	Open Closed Principle	Classes should be open for extension but closed for modification	Extend behavior without changing existing code
L	Liskov Substitution Principle	Child classes should replace parent classes without breaking code	Subclasses must behave like parent
I	Interface Segregation Principle	Clients should not depend on interfaces they don’t use	Small specific interfaces
D	Dependency Inversion Principle	High-level modules should depend on abstractions, not concrete classes	Depend on interfaces
1️⃣ Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)

A class should do only one thing.

❌ Bad Example

class UserService {

    public void saveUser() {
        // save user
    }

    public void sendEmail() {
        // send email
    }
}

This class has two responsibilities.

✔ Good Example

class UserService {
    public void saveUser() {}
}

class EmailService {
    public void sendEmail() {}
}

Each class now has one responsibility.

2️⃣ Open Closed Principle (OCP)

Software entities should be open for extension but closed for modification.

❌ Bad Example

class PaymentService {

    public void pay(String type) {

        if(type.equals("CreditCard")) {
            // logic
        }

        if(type.equals("UPI")) {
            // logic
        }
    }
}

Each new payment type requires modifying the class.

✔ Good Example

interface Payment {
    void pay();
}

class CreditCardPayment implements Payment {
    public void pay() {}
}

class UpiPayment implements Payment {
    public void pay() {}
}

Now we can add new payment methods without modifying existing code.

3️⃣ Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP)

Child classes should replace parent classes without breaking functionality.

❌ Bad Example

class Bird {
    void fly(){}
}

class Penguin extends Bird {
    void fly(){
        throw new RuntimeException("Cannot fly");
    }
}

Penguin cannot fly → breaks behavior.

✔ Good Design

class Bird {}

class FlyingBird extends Bird {
    void fly(){}
}

class Penguin extends Bird {}
4️⃣ Interface Segregation Principle (ISP)

Interfaces should be small and specific.

❌ Bad Example

interface Worker {

    void work();
    void eat();
}

Robot workers don't eat.

✔ Good Example

interface Workable {
    void work();
}

interface Eatable {
    void eat();
}

Now classes implement only what they need.

5️⃣ Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP)

High-level modules should depend on abstractions (interfaces), not concrete classes.

❌ Bad Example

class Car {

    Engine engine = new Engine();

}

Car directly depends on Engine.

✔ Good Example

interface Engine {
    void start();
}

class PetrolEngine implements Engine {
    public void start(){}
}

class Car {

    Engine engine;

    Car(Engine engine){
        this.engine = engine;
    }
}

Now Car depends on Engine interface, not a specific implementation.

This principle is heavily used in Spring Dependency Injection (@Autowired).
